<br>
<br>
In your PoG example, Tunare is not a multi-day rotation.  And even were she, one could argue that you could have left 2-3 groups clearing, and sent 2-3 groups for Ragefire and been able to do both.  Especially in regards to the old Ragefire setup - which I would pass Tunare for to keep one of my clerics in line (assuming Ragefire wasn't one groupable).<br>
<br>
<br>
As for N ToV, any time a guild gets less than 2/3 of the spawn, and the zone crashes, they are within their &quot;rights&quot; to ask for another turn at N ToV.  The 2/3 number was created to keep guilds from leaving the triplets up (for lack of wanting their risk vs reward) and then claiming they &quot;lost&quot; mobs to a server down (which yes, happened).  However, Aaryonar isn't 2/3, and if that is all you got up to (Feshlak and Vyemm included), you would be well within your &quot;rights&quot; to ask for a second shot at N ToV if a server crash happened.<br>
<br>
Your specific CT example is a shade of grey to me.  You didn't stop N ToV to run out and go kill a mob and then rush back to N ToV.  You were done for the night, and those members left on, went to go take out a rotation mob.  You then went back in and finished your second day.  Having done N ToV and VT countless times, I know that no matter how much you might like people to camp in the room for a fast start the next day, someone (actually many someones) will want to go to the bazaar, xp, arena, whatever, so there is ALWAYS a need to COH for day 2.  What you did, as you point out, didn't take any time from N ToV than you already would have (you had finished for the night), and still kept CT rotation moving.  However, I would put CT closer to the side of Statue/Trak than I would Emp or Cursed in difficulty.<br>
<br>
What the rule is meant to do, is keep people from, mid-evening, TLing their whole force out of VT and running to kill Emp, Cursed, Tallon, etc (mobs that require significant numbers and are on rotation), and holding the VT mobs &quot;hostage&quot;.  If those other mobs are so important you would dump VT Named mid-raid to go grab, then you should let the next guild up have their shot at the VT named.  (N ToV could be substituted for VT in my above example).  You are risking a server crash eating Aten because these other mobs are so important. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bogarthamule>Bogarthamule</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>VoF</span><br>  Posts: 148<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(5/22/03 5:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=342.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Some Curiosities about RTA Rules?</span><hr size=1> I understand the logic of keeping our priorities, as well as not losing the main named (Aten) in case of server crash (and we all know they come anyday anytime).  I totally agree that guilds should pick which mobs are important to them, and pass on ones that may not be.  Since the loot is SO much better in VT than NToV, I can see how that zone would probably raise more concern than NToV (though I guess NToV loot is great for many guilds).<br>
<br>
I don't really know VT at all, so I don't know the time needed to kill certain nameds and campable places for mages, etc.  I guess the biggest reason why I question the rule is because of the CT example I gave.  We usually camp at the back of Kreizenn's lair at the end of the first day.  It only takes a few hours max to kill the back 7 mobs from there, but let's say most everyone will be logging in an hour, then it's just best to stop after Kreizz and finish up those last few hours the next day (Granted it's possible to camp in Lady Mir's lair but more dangerous...also can camp in Lady Nev's lair but clearing to it and killing would take far longer).  So from that point on you are basically sitting there with an extra hour where you'd like to kill something, but strategically it doesn't make sense to go any further in NToV.  That was really the kind of situation I was thinking of that would make the rule unneeded.<br>
<br>
I guess I just figured that since that kind of thing was possible in NToV, it was probably so in VT as well (getting to a point with limited time left where it would take longer to finish than you have time left...going out and wacking a mob...and then returning the next day at the same place you would have had you killed the mob or not).  If it's more difficult to do that in VT, or just not logical to do, then I totally understand the need for the rule.  Since I have experience with NToV, I see that kind of situation can happen pretty easily, which is why I argued against the rule.<br>
<br>
